It's gone.

00:24:56.750 --> 00:24:58.600
If you put it in the bank, you
could've earned interest on

00:24:58.600 --> 00:24:59.580
that money.

00:24:59.580 --> 00:25:01.550
That's an opportunity cost. And
we'll come back and talk

00:25:01.550 --> 00:25:03.100
about capital markets
and interest later.

00:25:03.100 --> 00:25:04.630
But that's opportunity
cost. What else?

00:25:04.630 --> 00:25:05.190
There's one more.

00:25:05.190 --> 00:25:06.560
AUDIENCE: You could have
sold the computer.

00:25:06.560 --> 00:25:07.660
PROFESSOR: I could have
sold the computer.

00:25:07.660 --> 00:25:08.980
I gave it to him, and
he used it for free.

00:25:08.980 --> 00:25:11.980
But if I could have sold that
for $1,000, that's an

00:25:11.980 --> 00:25:13.780
opportunity cost as well.

00:25:13.780 --> 00:25:16.680
So, in fact, if I could have
worked for $60,000.

00:25:16.680 --> 00:25:20.520
On the $40,000, I could have
made $2,000 of interest. And I

00:25:20.520 --> 00:25:21.890
could have sold the computer
for $1,000.

00:25:21.890 --> 00:25:27.170
Then, actually, my opportunity
costs were $63,000 plus the

00:25:27.170 --> 00:25:28.820
$40,000 I paid the guy.

00:25:28.820 --> 00:25:31.880
So, actually, the entire cost of
the operation was $103,000.

00:25:31.880 --> 00:25:34.780
So I actually lost more than
$40,000 running my little

00:25:34.780 --> 00:25:36.870
website business.

00:25:36.870 --> 00:25:40.070
So opportunity costs represent
the fact that you could have

00:25:40.070 --> 00:25:41.820
done other things with
your resources.

00:25:41.820 --> 00:25:43.450
It's not just the fact
that your cash flow

00:25:43.450 --> 00:25:44.680
said positive $20,000.

00:25:44.680 --> 00:25:48.330
Your economic flow said
minus $43,000.

00:25:48.330 --> 00:25:50.770
Because while you're plus
$20,000, you were minus

00:25:50.770 --> 00:25:52.360
$60,000 that you could
have earned.

00:25:52.360 --> 00:25:53.380
Now you're down to
minus $40,000.

00:25:53.380 --> 00:25:54.830
You're minus $2,000 that you
could have earned in interest

00:25:54.830 --> 00:25:56.350
on the money you paid
the programmer.

00:25:56.350 --> 00:25:57.740
Now you're down to
minus $42,000.

00:25:57.740 --> 00:25:59.465
And you're down another minus
$1,000 you could have made by

00:25:59.465 --> 00:26:00.890
selling that computer.

00:26:00.890 --> 00:26:02.730
So you're at minus $43,000.

00:26:02.730 --> 00:26:04.190
So you actually lost money.

00:26:04.190 --> 00:26:07.770
So when we talk about profit,
we want to think about

00:26:07.770 --> 00:26:09.680
economic profit, not
accounting profit.

00:26:09.680 --> 00:26:12.850
Now, I'm not going to make that
distinction much now.

00:26:12.850 --> 00:26:15.230
But I want you to keep that in
mind as you go out and think

00:26:15.230 --> 00:26:16.740
about starting your business or
think about whether firms

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:19.710
are profitable, remember we use
an economic concept which

00:26:19.710 --> 00:26:22.640
accounts for opportunity cost,
not just an accounting concept

00:26:22.640 --> 00:26:25.740
which follows the dollars.

00:26:25.740 --> 00:26:27.660
Question about that?

00:26:27.660 --> 00:26:27.940
OK.

00:26:27.940 --> 00:26:32.090
Now, armed with this, we now
say, OK, how does a firm

00:26:32.090 --> 00:26:33.660
maximize profits?

00:26:33.660 --> 00:26:34.680
Well, that's easy.

00:26:34.680 --> 00:26:38.450
We say that profits is a
function of quantity produced.

00:26:38.450 --> 00:26:40.960
Revenues is a function of
quantity produced minus cost

00:26:40.960 --> 00:26:42.420
as a function of quantity
produced.

00:26:42.420 --> 00:26:44.260
Remember, what was our goal when
we laid out the start of

00:26:44.260 --> 00:26:45.070
this lecture?

00:26:45.070 --> 00:26:48.790
It was to figure out what
little q a firm chooses.

00:26:48.790 --> 00:26:52.640
Well, what little q a firm
chooses is dictated by

00:26:52.640 --> 00:26:53.950
maximizing this equation.

00:26:53.950 --> 00:27:02.140
So a firm will choose little q
such that dR/dq equals dC/dq.

00:27:02.140 --> 00:27:04.550
That's the profit maximizing
equation.

00:27:04.550 --> 00:27:08.680
A firm will choose its quantity
such that dR/dq

00:27:08.680 --> 00:27:15.490
equals dC/dq or, to put it in
economic terms, where marginal

00:27:15.490 --> 00:27:18.190
revenue equals marginal costs.

00:27:18.190 --> 00:27:22.110
The firm will choose to produce
a quantity q where its

00:27:22.110 --> 00:27:26.200
marginal revenue, which is the
revenue made from selling the

00:27:26.200 --> 00:27:29.160
next unit, equals it's marginal
cost, which is the

00:27:29.160 --> 00:27:33.860
cost incurred by making
the next unit.

00:27:33.860 --> 00:27:38.100
Well, in a competitive market,
we know what dR/dq is.

00:27:38.100 --> 00:27:40.360
Because remember in a
competitive market, dR/dq is

00:27:40.360 --> 00:27:42.380
given to the firm
by the market.

00:27:42.380 --> 00:27:45.590
In a competitive market, dR/dq,
or marginal revenue,

00:27:45.590 --> 00:27:47.520
equals the price.

00:27:47.520 --> 00:27:48.610
The price is given
to the firm.

00:27:48.610 --> 00:27:50.600
It comes from God in the
competitive market.

00:27:50.600 --> 00:27:51.820
We'll talk later about
where it comes from.

00:27:51.820 --> 00:27:53.890
But, for now, let's
consider it God.

00:27:53.890 --> 00:27:55.610
They're price takers.

00:27:55.610 --> 00:27:58.410
They just get some price
handed to them.

00:27:58.410 --> 00:28:00.950
So in a competitive market, we
know what marginal revenue is,

00:28:00.950 --> 00:28:01.850
it is price.

00:28:01.850 --> 00:28:05.740
So what this says is that in a
competitive market, the profit

00:28:05.740 --> 00:28:10.190
maximizing equation is price
equals marginal cost. Memorize

00:28:10.190 --> 00:28:12.800
it, put it under your pillow.

00:28:12.800 --> 00:28:15.970
In a competitive market, price
equals marginal cost is the

00:28:15.970 --> 00:28:17.840
profit maximizing condition.

00:28:17.840 --> 00:28:20.370
You will produce until the
marginal cost of producing the

00:28:20.370 --> 00:28:23.350
next unit is equal to the price
you can sell that unit

00:28:23.350 --> 00:28:24.600
for in the market.

00:28:26.990 --> 00:28:29.960
So, to see that further, let's
look at an example.

00:28:29.960 --> 00:28:37.390
Let's go to the next figure,
Figure 10-2a.

00:28:37.390 --> 00:28:39.260
For the next few examples,
I'm going to use a

00:28:39.260 --> 00:28:41.070
particular cost function.

00:28:41.070 --> 00:28:45.440
The cost function I'm going to
use to make this all concrete

00:28:45.440 --> 00:28:54.320
is C equals 10 plus
0.5q squared.

00:28:56.970 --> 00:28:59.470
That's the cost function
I'm going to use.

00:28:59.470 --> 00:29:03.040
So armed with that cost
function, let's say the price

00:29:03.040 --> 00:29:07.310
in the market is 6.

00:29:07.310 --> 00:29:09.010
Let's say the price
in the market 6.

00:29:09.010 --> 00:29:10.650
I just pulled that
out of my hat.

00:29:10.650 --> 00:29:11.640
It's a market for whatever.

00:29:11.640 --> 00:29:14.340
We're just doing an example.

00:29:14.340 --> 00:29:18.340
Now, what we have on this graph,
we have a cost curve

00:29:18.340 --> 00:29:19.790
and a revenue curve.

00:29:19.790 --> 00:29:22.010
The cost curve literally
graphs that function.

00:29:22.010 --> 00:29:26.290
So, in other words, if you
produce two units, then your

00:29:26.290 --> 00:29:30.440
cost is 10 plus half
of 2 squared or 12.

00:29:30.440 --> 00:29:34.060
If you produce 2 units, your
costs are 12, and so on.

00:29:34.060 --> 00:29:36.570
You've got this cost curve.

00:29:36.570 --> 00:29:38.190
You've also got a
revenue curve.

00:29:38.190 --> 00:29:40.860
Well, the revenue curve is just
6 times the number of

00:29:40.860 --> 00:29:41.360
units produced.

00:29:41.360 --> 00:29:42.930
Because the price
per unit is 6.

00:29:42.930 --> 00:29:47.150
So it's just a straight line
with a slope of 6.

00:29:47.150 --> 00:29:51.090
So each unit you produce,
you make 6.

00:29:51.090 --> 00:29:59.800
Now, what you'll see here is
that for this cost curve,

00:29:59.800 --> 00:30:01.290
what's marginal cost?

00:30:01.290 --> 00:30:03.970
Well, if we differentiate this,
we see that marginal

00:30:03.970 --> 00:30:06.380
cost equals q.

00:30:06.380 --> 00:30:07.880
I made this an easy example.

00:30:07.880 --> 00:30:09.230
If you differentiate that,
you'll see that

00:30:09.230 --> 00:30:11.130
marginal cost equals q.

00:30:11.130 --> 00:30:13.780
That is just differentiate
this cost equation.

00:30:13.780 --> 00:30:15.400
Marginal cost equals q.

00:30:15.400 --> 00:30:22.520
So what that says is that the
profit maximizing point is

00:30:22.520 --> 00:30:27.640
going to be to set marginal
cost equal to price.

00:30:27.640 --> 00:30:31.640
So that says set
q equal with 6.

00:30:31.640 --> 00:30:32.080
And you're done.

00:30:32.080 --> 00:30:33.460
That's how much the firm
should produce.

00:30:36.300 --> 00:30:39.650
The firm should produce six
units, because it's marginal

00:30:39.650 --> 00:30:41.250
cost function is q.

00:30:41.250 --> 00:30:43.950
It's a linear function.

00:30:43.950 --> 00:30:44.940
The price is six.

00:30:44.940 --> 00:30:47.030
That's a horizontal line.

00:30:47.030 --> 00:30:51.920
So they only intersect in one
point where quantity equals 6.

00:30:51.920 --> 00:30:56.110
Now, what you notice in this
graph is that this happens to

00:30:56.110 --> 00:30:59.400
be the point where the gap
between the revenue curve and

00:30:59.400 --> 00:31:04.280
the cost curve is largest. These
are not marginal curves.

00:31:04.280 --> 00:31:08.200
This is revenue and cost. But
notice that at 6 that's

00:31:08.200 --> 00:31:11.770
exactly where the revenue curve
and the cost curve have

00:31:11.770 --> 00:31:13.800
the largest gap between them.

00:31:13.800 --> 00:31:16.160
I think a more intuitive way
to see this is to flip to

00:31:16.160 --> 00:31:18.660
Figure 10-2b.

00:31:18.660 --> 00:31:24.030
This shows the marginal profit
that you make on

00:31:24.030 --> 00:31:25.510
every unit you sell.

00:31:25.510 --> 00:31:27.860
So, in other words, if you sell
fewer than 2 units, you

00:31:27.860 --> 00:31:29.050
lose money.

00:31:29.050 --> 00:31:29.690
Why?

00:31:29.690 --> 00:31:36.040
Because if you sell 1 unit, your
costs are 10 plus 10.5.

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:38.220
If you sell 1 unit, your
costs are 10.5.

00:31:38.220 --> 00:31:39.420
Your revenues are 6.

00:31:39.420 --> 00:31:40.400
You lose money.

00:31:40.400 --> 00:31:42.150
You lose 4.5.

00:31:42.150 --> 00:31:44.320
If you sell 2 units,
you make 0.

00:31:44.320 --> 00:31:46.730
Your costs are 12, your
revenues are 12.

00:31:46.730 --> 00:31:48.440
You make 0.

00:31:48.440 --> 00:31:54.120
If you sell 3 units, your
costs are 14.5, 10

00:31:54.120 --> 00:31:56.130
plus half of 9.

00:31:56.130 --> 00:31:57.570
Your revenues are 18.

00:31:57.570 --> 00:31:59.460
So you make money.

00:31:59.460 --> 00:32:03.020
So each unit, you can calculate
how much you're

00:32:03.020 --> 00:32:04.620
making on that next unit.

00:32:04.620 --> 00:32:06.780
On the 3rd unit,
you made money.

00:32:06.780 --> 00:32:09.340
4th unit, you make
even more money.

00:32:09.340 --> 00:32:10.270
5th unit, even more.

00:32:10.270 --> 00:32:13.230
6th unit, you make the most
money you can make.

00:32:13.230 --> 00:32:17.290
In the 6th unit, your costs
are 10 plus half of

00:32:17.290 --> 00:32:21.240
36, or 18, so 28.

00:32:21.240 --> 00:32:22.690
Your costs are 28.

00:32:22.690 --> 00:32:24.390
Your revenues are 36.

00:32:24.390 --> 00:32:27.610
So you make a profit of 8.

00:32:27.610 --> 00:32:29.860
You make a profit of
8 on that 6th unit.

00:32:32.700 --> 00:32:34.870
Think of yourself as
climbing this hill.

00:32:34.870 --> 00:32:37.730
In economics, optimization is
a hill climbing exercise.

00:32:37.730 --> 00:32:40.820
Think of yourself as climbing
up this hill and asking

00:32:40.820 --> 00:32:42.460
yourself, should I make
the next unit?

00:32:42.460 --> 00:32:43.800
Does the hill keep going up?

00:32:43.800 --> 00:32:44.610
Yes, it keeps going up.

00:32:44.610 --> 00:32:46.120
Make that next unit.

00:32:46.120 --> 00:32:47.090
Then you get to the top.

00:32:47.090 --> 00:32:49.070
And now you say, well, should
I make the 7th unit?

00:32:49.070 --> 00:32:52.560
Well if I make a 7th unit,
my costs are 10 plus

00:32:52.560 --> 00:32:57.550
half of 49, so 34.5.

00:32:57.550 --> 00:33:00.410
My revenues are 42.

00:33:00.410 --> 00:33:03.220
So my profits are only 7.5.

00:33:03.220 --> 00:33:06.810
I make less profit
on that 7th unit.

00:33:06.810 --> 00:33:09.910
So I shouldn't make it.

00:33:09.910 --> 00:33:11.240
Now, you might say,
wait a second.

00:33:14.700 --> 00:33:16.790
Why wouldn't you make it?

00:33:16.790 --> 00:33:18.830
You still make profits.

00:33:18.830 --> 00:33:21.340
Why wouldn't you go ahead and
make all units all the way

00:33:21.340 --> 00:33:23.050
down to 10?

00:33:23.050 --> 00:33:25.330
You still make profits
on those units.

00:33:25.330 --> 00:33:28.670
And the answer is because of
opportunity cost. The answer

00:33:28.670 --> 00:33:31.260
is that yes, you make profits.

00:33:31.260 --> 00:33:34.850
But given where your marginal
cost curve is, you could do

00:33:34.850 --> 00:33:38.440
better by that point going and
producing other goods.

00:33:38.440 --> 00:33:40.220
That's why I care about
accounting costs versus

00:33:40.220 --> 00:33:41.310
opportunity costs.

00:33:41.310 --> 00:33:44.050
Accounting costs says look,
you're going to make money

00:33:44.050 --> 00:33:46.960
until you go to 10 units.

00:33:46.960 --> 00:33:49.460
But opportunity cost says, no.

00:33:49.460 --> 00:33:53.000
At that point, the opportunity
cost has gotten high enough

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:54.300
that you could do
better devoting

00:33:54.300 --> 00:33:55.980
your resources elsewhere.

00:33:55.980 --> 00:33:58.075
And that's why you want to stop
at the point where you're

00:33:58.075 --> 00:34:00.810
at the top of the hill, where
the price equals the marginal

00:34:00.810 --> 00:34:04.250
cost.

00:34:04.250 --> 00:34:07.540
So what are the profits you make
at the top of this hill?

00:34:07.540 --> 00:34:11.830
Well, if you go to the next
diagram, we can see what the

00:34:11.830 --> 00:34:13.719
profits you make are.

00:34:13.719 --> 00:34:17.659
So this next diagram,
Figure 10-3,

00:34:17.659 --> 00:34:19.600
illustrates this example.

00:34:19.600 --> 00:34:22.030
So what we have here is an
example with cost curves for

00:34:22.030 --> 00:34:26.290
this cost function, once again,
10 plus 0.5q squared.

00:34:26.290 --> 00:34:30.389
Average costs is that line
in the middle there.

00:34:30.389 --> 00:34:32.260
That's the average costs.

00:34:32.260 --> 00:34:35.560
You have an average variable
cost that's a line, that's

00:34:35.560 --> 00:34:40.350
linear, an average variable cost
that has a slope of one.

00:34:40.350 --> 00:34:42.730
You have an average fixed cost
that's everywhere declining,

00:34:42.730 --> 00:34:44.969
because your fixed costs of 10
is everywhere declining.

00:34:44.969 --> 00:34:46.000
As you produce more
and more, your

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:47.120
fixed costs are declining.

00:34:47.120 --> 00:34:50.409
And, as I said, you have
a marginal cost of q.

00:34:50.409 --> 00:34:53.389
So your marginal cost
of 1 unit is 1.

00:34:53.389 --> 00:34:57.420
Your marginal cost of 2
units is 2, et cetera.

00:34:57.420 --> 00:35:01.290
So this draws out the cost
curves that correspond to that

00:35:01.290 --> 00:35:03.200
cost function.

00:35:03.200 --> 00:35:05.280
You see them drawn out here.

00:35:05.280 --> 00:35:10.090
Now, we also, on this diagram,
have a demand curve.

00:35:10.090 --> 00:35:12.910
The demand curve is perfectly
elastic facing this firm.

00:35:12.910 --> 00:35:15.530
It's a perfectly competitive
market.

00:35:15.530 --> 00:35:20.030
And that perfectly elastic
demand curve is horizontal at

00:35:20.030 --> 00:35:23.520
price equals 6.

00:35:23.520 --> 00:35:25.780
So what does the firm do?

00:35:25.780 --> 00:35:33.720
It chooses to produce where
marginal cost equals price.

00:35:33.720 --> 00:35:36.710
When it produces where marginal
cost equals price,

00:35:36.710 --> 00:35:38.810
then what profits
does it make?

00:35:48.510 --> 00:35:50.670
On each unit, it makes a
difference of the profits

00:35:50.670 --> 00:35:53.870
between the price and average
cost. Now it's an important

00:35:53.870 --> 00:35:54.780
distinction.

00:35:54.780 --> 00:35:56.090
We went over this in lecture
and section.

00:35:56.090 --> 00:35:57.490
But let me go through
it again.

00:35:57.490 --> 00:36:00.420
Marginal cost is the cost
of the next unit.

00:36:00.420 --> 00:36:02.265
Average cost is the average
cost of all the

00:36:02.265 --> 00:36:04.040
units you've made.

00:36:04.040 --> 00:36:08.240
So if I make 6 units, what
profit do I make?

00:36:08.240 --> 00:36:15.740
Well, on that 6th unit, I
make a profit of 1 and

00:36:15.740 --> 00:36:25.700
1/8 or 1 and 1/4.

00:36:31.925 --> 00:36:36.380
I make profits of 1 and
1/4 on that 6th unit.

00:36:36.380 --> 00:36:41.020
But I make those profits
on all 8 units I sell.

00:36:41.020 --> 00:36:44.770
So what that means is, in total,
I'm going to make a

00:36:44.770 --> 00:36:45.970
profit of 8.

00:36:45.970 --> 00:36:49.330
The area of this rectangle
is eight.

00:36:49.330 --> 00:36:50.790
Here's the key.

00:36:50.790 --> 00:36:53.900
You cannot choose a production
level that produces a bigger

00:36:53.900 --> 00:36:56.270
rectangle than this.

00:36:56.270 --> 00:36:59.970
So if you produce 7, your
rectangle will be longer.

00:36:59.970 --> 00:37:03.910
But the gap between price and
average cost will be smaller.

00:37:03.910 --> 00:37:07.240
So your total rectangle
size would fall.

00:37:07.240 --> 00:37:10.580
The largest rectangle
is produced at a

00:37:10.580 --> 00:37:12.390
production level of 6.

00:37:12.390 --> 00:37:15.610
That's the most efficient use of
your resources is when you

00:37:15.610 --> 00:37:18.790
produce at a point where
marginal cost equals price.

00:37:18.790 --> 00:37:21.060
Because when you produce at
marginal cost equals price,

00:37:21.060 --> 00:37:25.620
that causes the maximum gap
between price and average

00:37:25.620 --> 00:37:26.020
cost.

00:37:26.020 --> 00:37:29.150
Flip back for a second
to the first figure.

00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:35.380
Not the first figure,
I'm sorry, 10-2.

00:37:35.380 --> 00:37:37.170
This relates back to 10-2.

00:37:37.170 --> 00:37:40.510
As I noted, the largest
difference between your

00:37:40.510 --> 00:37:45.110
revenue and your cost curve
was that 6 units.

00:37:45.110 --> 00:37:47.510
That's where the gap is large
between revenue and cost.

00:37:47.510 --> 00:37:48.770
That's where you produce.

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:52.510
Now we flip forward again
to Figure 10-3.

00:37:52.510 --> 00:37:56.930
You see that corresponds to the
point of the largest gap

00:37:56.930 --> 00:38:05.790
between price and average cost,
I'm sorry, the largest

00:38:05.790 --> 00:38:09.260
of the points on the marginal
cost curve between price and

00:38:09.260 --> 00:38:12.100
average cost. So if you produce
on the marginal cost

00:38:12.100 --> 00:38:17.460
curve, if you produce 7 units,
then you're going to have a

00:38:17.460 --> 00:38:20.500
smaller gap between price and
average cost. And, therefore,

00:38:20.500 --> 00:38:22.100
even though you produced 1
more unit and are making

00:38:22.100 --> 00:38:25.830
profit on it, your total
profits will fall.

00:38:25.830 --> 00:38:29.090
The key point is that yes,
climbing back down that hill I

00:38:29.090 --> 00:38:30.420
still make money.

00:38:30.420 --> 00:38:33.670
But I make less and
less money.

00:38:33.670 --> 00:38:36.670
And that, as a result, that
rectangle is being reduced as

00:38:36.670 --> 00:38:38.230
I climb down that hill.

00:38:38.230 --> 00:38:40.920
That rectangle is maximized
at the top of that hill.

00:38:40.920 --> 00:38:44.680
That's the point at which
I make the most money.

00:38:44.680 --> 00:38:54.750
So that's why we say profit
maximization occurs at the

00:38:54.750 --> 00:38:56.970
point where price equals
marginal cost. Because that is

00:38:56.970 --> 00:39:01.360
the point of greatest gap
between revenues and costs.

00:39:01.360 --> 00:39:02.910
Where price equals marginal cost
is one of the greatest

00:39:02.910 --> 00:39:04.220
gaps between revenues
and costs.

00:39:04.220 --> 00:39:06.490
That's the profit maximizing
point where that rectangle is

00:39:06.490 --> 00:39:08.260
largest. And you can demonstrate
for yourself, and

00:39:08.260 --> 00:39:11.030
you should, that at any other
production level, that

00:39:11.030 --> 00:39:13.970
rectangle will be smaller.

00:39:13.970 --> 00:39:14.880
Questions about that?

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:15.820
Yeah.

00:39:15.820 --> 00:39:17.856
AUDIENCE: What do you
do if you have

00:39:17.856 --> 00:39:19.110
a linear cost function.

00:39:19.110 --> 00:39:21.460
So that means marginal
cost is a constant.

00:39:21.460 --> 00:39:23.960
Then how do you determine
the line?

00:39:23.960 --> 00:39:25.210
PROFESSOR: You don't.

00:39:27.310 --> 00:39:28.590
It's an indeterminacy.

00:39:28.590 --> 00:39:29.490
That's right.

00:39:29.490 --> 00:39:31.170
I'll try to avoid giving
you problems like that.

00:39:31.170 --> 00:39:33.340
Basically you get a
corner solution.

00:39:33.340 --> 00:39:35.890
In a perfectly competitive
market, you'd get an

00:39:35.890 --> 00:39:36.920
indeterminate solution.

00:39:36.920 --> 00:39:38.460
In a nonperfectly competitive
market, you will have a

00:39:38.460 --> 00:39:39.900
determinant solution.

00:39:39.900 --> 00:39:42.610
But in a perfectly competitive
market with a linear marginal

00:39:42.610 --> 00:39:44.180
cost, you'd have an
indeterminate solution.

00:39:44.180 --> 00:39:46.230
Either you produce
0 or infinity.

00:39:46.230 --> 00:39:47.700
So you'd have an indeterminate
solution.

00:39:50.570 --> 00:39:54.230
Now, just a further drill this
in, imagine, for a second,

00:39:54.230 --> 00:39:57.140
there was a cost shock
to the firm.

00:39:57.140 --> 00:39:59.110
Imagine there was a cost
shock to the firm.

00:39:59.110 --> 00:40:03.590
Imagine that there's a tax on
the firm where the firm has to

00:40:03.590 --> 00:40:05.170
pay a tax of an amount t.

00:40:05.170 --> 00:40:07.590
Let's say t is $1.

00:40:07.590 --> 00:40:13.740
The firm has to pay a tax of $1
on every unit they produce.

00:40:13.740 --> 00:40:15.880
Well, what is their
new cost curve?

00:40:15.880 --> 00:40:17.960
Somebody tell me what the
new cost curve is.

00:40:17.960 --> 00:40:20.640
If you have a tax of $1 on
every unit you produce,

00:40:20.640 --> 00:40:23.020
someone tell me the equation
for the cost curve.

00:40:23.020 --> 00:40:24.440
I didn't write it down
here, did I?

00:40:24.440 --> 00:40:24.890
No.

00:40:24.890 --> 00:40:27.590
OK, what's the equation
for the cost curve.

00:40:27.590 --> 00:40:28.320
Yeah.

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:32.160
AUDIENCE: Just add plus
tq to the top thing.

00:40:32.160 --> 00:40:40.840
PROFESSOR: Exactly C equals 10
plus 0.5q squared plus tq.

00:40:40.840 --> 00:40:43.660
Because for every unit you
produce q you pay a tax t.

00:40:43.660 --> 00:40:46.550
And since t is $1, it would
just be plus q.

00:40:46.550 --> 00:40:49.140
If t is $1, it would
just be plus q.

00:40:49.140 --> 00:40:52.760
So the cost function
has now shifted.

00:40:52.760 --> 00:40:55.660
So what we see is that it has
shifted average cost and

00:40:55.660 --> 00:40:59.120
marginal cost both upwards.

00:40:59.120 --> 00:41:02.520
Average cost has shifted
upwards by that amount.

00:41:02.520 --> 00:41:04.870
And average cost has
shifted upwards.

00:41:04.870 --> 00:41:07.950
And marginal cost has shifted
upwards by precisely $1.

00:41:07.950 --> 00:41:09.590
It's just a linear shift of
marginal cost. Because

00:41:09.590 --> 00:41:15.380
marginal cost is now q plus 1.

00:41:15.380 --> 00:41:19.160
If you differentiate this with
respect to q assuming t is 1--

00:41:19.160 --> 00:41:20.350
t is now $1--

00:41:20.350 --> 00:41:22.500
if you differentiate this with
respect to q, marginal

00:41:22.500 --> 00:41:24.320
cost is q plus 1.

00:41:24.320 --> 00:41:29.060
So your marginal cost curve has
shifted up by $1 or by t,

00:41:29.060 --> 00:41:32.790
in this case, in the
more general case.

00:41:32.790 --> 00:41:36.570
Well, what does that do to the
first production decision.

00:41:36.570 --> 00:41:40.910
Well, now it doesn't change
their maximization formula.

00:41:40.910 --> 00:41:43.410
They still want to set marginal
cost equal to price.

00:41:43.410 --> 00:41:47.730
So now they say, set q plus
1 equal to price.

00:41:47.730 --> 00:41:49.590
Well, the price is 6.

00:41:49.590 --> 00:41:53.100
So it says set q equal to 5.

00:41:53.100 --> 00:41:58.450
Now the profit maximizing
level is 5 units.

00:41:58.450 --> 00:42:00.600
The profit maximizing
level is 5 units.

00:42:05.270 --> 00:42:07.450
What this is saying is because
the tax increases your

00:42:07.450 --> 00:42:11.970
marginal cost, you are
now producing less.

00:42:11.970 --> 00:42:14.310
And what we can see now, if we
flip to Figure 10-4, we can

00:42:14.310 --> 00:42:16.260
see what that's done
to your profits.

00:42:16.260 --> 00:42:24.580
Your profits have now fallen to
the dotted rectangle, the

00:42:24.580 --> 00:42:27.750
much smaller dotted rectangle.

00:42:27.750 --> 00:42:29.900
Your profits used to be
that entire slashed

00:42:29.900 --> 00:42:32.160
rectangle plus the dots.

00:42:32.160 --> 00:42:37.800
Now your profits are just
where the price exceeds

00:42:37.800 --> 00:42:41.690
average cost which is just that
smaller dotted rectangle.

00:42:41.690 --> 00:42:43.690
Your profits have fallen
dramatically.

00:42:43.690 --> 00:42:47.140
So by imposing a tax on this
firm, we've dramatically

00:42:47.140 --> 00:42:48.390
reduced their profits.

00:42:52.050 --> 00:42:56.870
Now, this is the economics
behind why taxes can lower

00:42:56.870 --> 00:42:58.960
production.

00:42:58.960 --> 00:43:00.910
Now, you might say,
wait a second.

00:43:00.910 --> 00:43:02.830
In reality, if we tax a
firm, the don't have

00:43:02.830 --> 00:43:03.260
to lower their profits.

00:43:03.260 --> 00:43:06.290
They just pass it on and charge
consumers higher prices

00:43:06.290 --> 00:43:08.550
but not in a competitive
market.

00:43:08.550 --> 00:43:10.660
In a competitive market,
they can't do that.

00:43:14.250 --> 00:43:15.896
If you tax a firm in a
competitive market, it comes

00:43:15.896 --> 00:43:17.146
out of their profits.

00:43:19.530 --> 00:43:22.015
Because they face a perfectly
elastic demand, so they can't

00:43:22.015 --> 00:43:23.020
raise the price.

00:43:23.020 --> 00:43:25.360
All they can do is just say,
well, the price is the same.

00:43:25.360 --> 00:43:26.920
My marginal cost has gone up.

00:43:26.920 --> 00:43:29.870
I'm going to produce less, and
I'm going to make less profit.

00:43:29.870 --> 00:43:31.900
And that's life.

00:43:31.900 --> 00:43:34.390
So a tax in a market like this
is just going to lower the

00:43:34.390 --> 00:43:36.710
firm's profits, and it's going
to lower their level of

00:43:36.710 --> 00:43:39.210
production from 6 to 5.

00:43:39.210 --> 00:43:40.882
In noncompetitive markets,
different things can happen.

00:43:40.882 --> 00:43:42.000
We'll talk about that.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:43.320
But in a competitive market,
this is what

00:43:43.320 --> 00:43:44.710
happens with the tax.

00:43:44.710 --> 00:43:48.260
You basically set the new
marginal cost equal to price,

00:43:48.260 --> 00:43:50.940
and you get that they produce
5 units instead of 6 at a

00:43:50.940 --> 00:43:52.630
lower profit level.

00:43:52.630 --> 00:43:53.592
Yeah?

00:43:53.592 --> 00:43:54.772
AUDIENCE: Would that
be a good cause for

00:43:54.772 --> 00:43:56.424
entering the market--

00:43:59.750 --> 00:44:00.040
PROFESSOR: You're right.

00:44:00.040 --> 00:44:03.530
That's an excellent point that
I should have pointed out.

00:44:03.530 --> 00:44:04.770
What do I mean by short run?

00:44:04.770 --> 00:44:07.420
What I mean by short run is
remember, labor is variable.

00:44:07.420 --> 00:44:08.470
Capital is fixed.

00:44:08.470 --> 00:44:09.650
What do I mean in
this context?

00:44:09.650 --> 00:44:11.510
Think about the short run as
being the period over time

00:44:11.510 --> 00:44:13.035
over which firms cannot
enter and exit.

00:44:15.980 --> 00:44:18.450
When we talk about competitive
markets in the short run, we

00:44:18.450 --> 00:44:20.550
talked about short run
being the time in

00:44:20.550 --> 00:44:21.780
which capital is fixed.

00:44:21.780 --> 00:44:23.190
Now we're going to add
another condition.

00:44:23.190 --> 00:44:25.090
We're going to say the short run
is the period of time in

00:44:25.090 --> 00:44:31.830
which there's no firm
entry or exit.

00:44:31.830 --> 00:44:32.520
That's the short run.

00:44:32.520 --> 00:44:34.730
We'll come back and talk about
what entry and exit does.

00:44:34.730 --> 00:44:36.510
And that's going to have
some funky effects.

00:44:36.510 --> 00:44:38.000
We'll talk about
that next time.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:39.920
But what we mean by short
run here is no

00:44:39.920 --> 00:44:40.680
firm entry and exit.

00:44:40.680 --> 00:44:44.510
Whichever firms are in the
market at the beginning of the

00:44:44.510 --> 00:44:46.040
short run people are in the
market at the end of the short

00:44:46.040 --> 00:44:46.430
run period.

00:44:46.430 --> 00:44:47.315
Yeah.

00:44:47.315 --> 00:44:49.343
AUDIENCE: But in your
conditions, you had like free

00:44:49.343 --> 00:44:51.250
and fluid entry and
exit of firms.

00:44:51.250 --> 00:44:51.910
PROFESSOR: Right, exactly.

00:44:51.910 --> 00:44:54.810
And that's why I said, don't
pay attention to that yet.

00:44:54.810 --> 00:44:56.190
In some sense, those are the
conditions of perfect

00:44:56.190 --> 00:44:56.670
competition.

00:44:56.670 --> 00:44:58.090
I didn't say if that was
short run or long run.

00:44:58.090 --> 00:45:00.270
Those are the full long
run set of conditions.

00:45:00.270 --> 00:45:02.220
That's why I said we're going
to ignore four for now and

00:45:02.220 --> 00:45:03.530
just focus on the first three.

00:45:03.530 --> 00:45:05.720
In the short run, only the
first three are relevant.

00:45:05.720 --> 00:45:07.790
Because in the short run there's
no firm entry or exit.

00:45:07.790 --> 00:45:09.670
In the long run, which we'll
talk about next time, that

00:45:09.670 --> 00:45:12.020
fourth one will be relevant.

00:45:12.020 --> 00:45:12.720
Good question.

00:45:12.720 --> 00:45:13.320
That's a good point.

00:45:13.320 --> 00:45:14.830
Thank you for pointing
that out.

00:45:14.830 --> 00:45:17.400
Other questions or comments?

00:45:17.400 --> 00:45:20.240
One other thing I want to cover
before we stop which

00:45:20.240 --> 00:45:24.970
relates to the long run, is that
in the long run, this is

00:45:24.970 --> 00:45:26.340
sort of the transition,
the bridge to talking

00:45:26.340 --> 00:45:27.840
about the long run.

00:45:27.840 --> 00:45:31.570
We also have to decide,
ultimately, whether or not we

00:45:31.570 --> 00:45:34.730
want to shut the firm down.

00:45:34.730 --> 00:45:36.890
So, in other words, we want to
set price equal to marginal

00:45:36.890 --> 00:45:38.530
cost. That's one condition.

00:45:38.530 --> 00:45:40.710
But, actually, short run profit
maximization has a

00:45:40.710 --> 00:45:42.040
second condition.

00:45:42.040 --> 00:45:44.720
Short run profit maximization
has two conditions.

00:45:44.720 --> 00:45:48.190
The first is to set price equal
to marginal cost. The

00:45:48.190 --> 00:45:51.490
second condition of short run
profit maximization is to

00:45:51.490 --> 00:45:53.920
check whether the firm
wants to shut down.

00:45:56.860 --> 00:45:58.170
Why would a firm want
to shut down?

00:45:58.170 --> 00:46:02.080
It might want to shut down if
it actually loses money by

00:46:02.080 --> 00:46:03.330
continuing to produce.

00:46:06.120 --> 00:46:12.540
And that's because firms may
lose money but not shut down.

00:46:12.540 --> 00:46:14.600
Firms may lose money
but not shut down.

00:46:14.600 --> 00:46:17.090
Or firms may lose so much
money they shut down.

00:46:17.090 --> 00:46:19.520
And we need to consider that.

00:46:22.760 --> 00:46:23.700
Let's get rid of the tax.

00:46:23.700 --> 00:46:26.390
Let's go back to the marginal
cost with the tax.

00:46:26.390 --> 00:46:28.040
Imagine the price in this
market suddenly

00:46:28.040 --> 00:46:30.560
fell from 6 to 3.

00:46:30.560 --> 00:46:35.350
The price of the market is
now $3 per unit you sell.

00:46:35.350 --> 00:46:37.835
Well what would the
firm's profits be?

00:46:37.835 --> 00:46:42.060
Well, if the price fell to 3,
the firm would choose to

00:46:42.060 --> 00:46:43.790
produce 3 units.

00:46:43.790 --> 00:46:46.480
You would still have this
condition, marginal cost

00:46:46.480 --> 00:46:46.970
equals price.

00:46:46.970 --> 00:46:48.580
Price is 3, and marginal
cost is q.

00:46:48.580 --> 00:46:49.960
So q is 3.

00:46:49.960 --> 00:46:52.650
You still produce 3 units.

00:46:52.650 --> 00:46:54.970
If you produce 3 units,
its costs are 10 plus

00:46:54.970 --> 00:46:58.530
4.5 which is 14.5.

00:46:58.530 --> 00:47:01.250
At a price of 3, it makes 9.

00:47:01.250 --> 00:47:05.360
So its profits are
negative 5.5.

00:47:05.360 --> 00:47:08.370
It would lose money from
this production.

00:47:12.660 --> 00:47:14.640
Remember marginal cost
equals price.

00:47:14.640 --> 00:47:18.160
That doesn't vary with what
the price is or anything.

00:47:18.160 --> 00:47:20.680
This is a maximizing
condition.

00:47:20.680 --> 00:47:22.770
If a price changed, it's not
like you change which equation

00:47:22.770 --> 00:47:23.080
you follow.

00:47:23.080 --> 00:47:24.500
You always follow
this equation.

00:47:24.500 --> 00:47:26.800
The efficient production level
is always marginal cost equals

00:47:26.800 --> 00:47:29.330
price regardless of
what the price is.

00:47:29.330 --> 00:47:31.800
So if the price is 3, the
efficient thing to do would be

00:47:31.800 --> 00:47:35.710
to produce 3 units
and lose money.

00:47:35.710 --> 00:47:38.610
Now, you might say, well,
then that's stupid.

00:47:38.610 --> 00:47:41.300
If that goes negative, wouldn't
they just shut down?

00:47:41.300 --> 00:47:44.070
And the answer, is in
the short run, no.

00:47:44.070 --> 00:47:46.530
And the reason you wouldn't shut
down in the short run is

00:47:46.530 --> 00:47:51.270
what I talked about last time
which is about the notion of

00:47:51.270 --> 00:47:53.680
sunk costs.

00:47:53.680 --> 00:47:57.350
In the short run, the fixed
costs that you paid

00:47:57.350 --> 00:47:58.830
to produce are sunk.

00:47:58.830 --> 00:48:00.560
They're unchangeable
in the short run.

00:48:00.560 --> 00:48:02.040
In the long run, they're
changeable.

00:48:02.040 --> 00:48:03.390
You can just leave.

00:48:03.390 --> 00:48:06.430
But in the short run, you've
invested fixed costs of 10 in

00:48:06.430 --> 00:48:07.600
being in this market.

00:48:07.600 --> 00:48:11.520
You've paid a fixed cost of 10
to produce in this market.

00:48:11.520 --> 00:48:17.200
Given you're in this market, and
you've paid 10 to produce,

00:48:17.200 --> 00:48:22.010
you will not exit unless
you lose more than $10.

00:48:22.010 --> 00:48:27.670
You will not shut down unless
you lose more than $10.

00:48:27.670 --> 00:48:30.480
You will not shut down unless
you're losing so much money

00:48:30.480 --> 00:48:32.510
that you can't cover
your fixed costs.

00:48:32.510 --> 00:48:34.380
Because you've paid those fixed
cost. In the short run,

00:48:34.380 --> 00:48:36.280
they're sunk.

00:48:36.280 --> 00:48:40.180
So unless you're actually losing
more than your fixed

00:48:40.180 --> 00:48:44.740
costs, you will not shut
down your firm.

00:48:44.740 --> 00:48:45.770
OK.

00:48:45.770 --> 00:48:47.145
This is actually pretty
confusing, and

00:48:47.145 --> 00:48:47.680
we're out of time.

00:48:47.680 --> 00:48:50.410
So what I'm going to do is we'll
pick it up on Monday

00:48:50.410 --> 00:48:51.870
exactly at this point.

00:48:51.870 --> 00:48:53.670
And I'll go through some more
of the intuition for this.

00:48:53.670 --> 00:48:56.180
And that will be our segue for
talking long run profit

00:48:56.180 --> 00:48:58.710
maximization which we'll
talk about on Monday.

